Diagnosis :—This species is most similar to
Myrcia neoobscura E. Lucas & C. E. Wilson
(in
Lucas et al. 2016: 680
), from which it is distinguished by having the midvein of leaf blade glabrous below (versus strigose in
M. neoobscura
), glaucous fruits (vs. blackish), and 5–6 calyx lobes (vs. 4 in
M. neoobscura
).
